{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":1505,"record_hash":"sha256:e1fc7923e4d3f236511cefb4687b870a4df9e0c0c17af57c820aa825341e0d44","timestamp":"2026-05-21T03:24:40.226Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yeah, `review` is GitButler’s review object, not “do a code review.”\n\nIn this command:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions review <review-id-or-key>\n```\n\n`review` means “find agent sessions related to a GitButler review / PR-like review entity.” It parallels:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions branch <branch>\nbut agentlog sessions change <change-id>\n```\n\nSo the target kinds are:\n\n- `branch`: related to a branch ref\n- `review`: related to a GitButler review key, like `gitbutler-review:<id>` or accepted shorthand\n- `change`: related to a GitButler change id\n\nI agree the word is ambiguous in an agent context because “review” reads like an action. Better CLI names might be:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions for-review <id>\nbut agentlog sessions target review <id>\nbut agentlog sessions --review <id>\n```\n\nBut since the existing shape is `sessions <target-kind> <value>`, I’d probably keep it for consistency unless we want to revisit the command shape before it becomes public.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T03:24:40.226Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}